MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, how are you feeling? Seats OK?
Roger, feeling good, all strapped in.
Sounds good. Once again, you are the first to fly it, {{profileName}}! We are all excited for the mission and seeing this state-of-the-art spacecraft fly.
So are we Patrick. {{coPilotName}} and I will proceed with the cockpit setup.
Roger. FLIGHT and MCC are all ready. Follow procedures.
Right {{coPilotName}}, you heard them. Let's get this thing ready for flight.
Right. First we will inspect the cockpit and set up the remaining switches so we are ready to perform pre-launch system tests. Use the RUN feature and complete the Interior Inspection checklist.
Checklist complete.
Roger. Timescale to T-50 minutes and then proceed with the Battery Check and the Fuel Cell check.
Roger, let's complete the Battery Check at T -50 minutes. Use the RUN feature and complete the Battery Check checklist.
Checklist complete, proceeding to the Fuel Cell check.
Roger, Fuel Cell check. Use the RUN feature and complete the Fuel Cell Check checklist.
Checklist complete.
We are preparing for the Squib and Abort test. Please proceed with the checklist, and when ready for the test, request the Squib & Abort Test using the COMMs menu.
Roger, will start with the Squib & Abort Check checklist.
Use the RUN feature and complete the Squib & Abort checklist.
Checklist completed.
Roger. We will switch to internal power at T-15 minutes. Walk through the BRIEFING in the Mission Pad and use timescale if you feel like it.
Roger, will do.
{{capsuleName}}, we are ready for the switch to Full Internal Power. Complete the checklist using the RUN feature.
Checklist complete.
Roger, prepare to RUN the Pre-Flight checklist at T-5 minutes.
Roger.
Complete the Pre-Flight checklist and prepare for flight.
Roger, running through the checklist.
Monitoring the platform alignment towards planned launch azimuth on the FDAI is crucial.
Roger, countdown proceeding as planned. Start following the ascent checklist.
Ok, double check that the platform is aligned and OK. The rocket will roll into planned azimuth and start pitching into orbit. Keep your hand on the D-Ring.
Yeah, we got this. Can't wait to see that Earth horizon again!
30 seconds.
Let's light this candle!
This is it.
Liftoff!
Roger, verify clocks are running!
That's a lot of shaking!
Entering Abort Mode I-II
All good, let's ride this Titan into orbit!
Abort Mode II.
Roger Abort Mode II.
Prepare for staging.
There goes Stage I!
Roger, staging.
Look at that horizon.
Welcome to space, {{coPilotName}}.
We have good visual of Earth, and the spacecraft seems to be OK.
Roger, you are doing great.
Cutoff! Separating from the launch vehicle.
Separation, jettisoning the scanner covers.
I can see the cover, 90 seconds to horizon scanner acquisition.
Enable the OAMS and "zero" the forward and back section of the IVIs. Press ROGER when complete.
Complete the INSERTION checklist using the RUN feature.
Roger, running checklist.
Verify computer is set to CATCH-UP and that the AUX TAPE LOAD indicator is green, meaning the tape is in motion.
Computer is at CATCH-UP.
Ok, we are uplinking an OBC update with the target parameters of the new circular orbit. The burn will take place at Pe in about {{timeToPe}}.
Roger. Will prepare for a circularization burn at the next Pe passing, in about {{timeToPe}}.
Roger. If you feel too pressured, the burn can take place at the Ap passing of the next orbit, just follow the circularization checklist manually.
Ok, you know the drill. Verify the OBC cores and reference the Circularize Orbit checklist.
Burn will start at Pe, and will lower Ap. Keep an eye on the time to Pe. I will prepare for the burn, let me know when it's 5 minutes to burn and enable OAMS.
Roger, powering the controller for OAMS.
OAMS ready. Set the S/C to SEF.
Roger, will do.
S/C to SEF. Burn will be retrograde using forward thrusters. Translate backwards in SEF to lower Apogee at Perigee.
5 minutes to Pe. Prepare for the burn. If you need to wait for the next passing, use the Circularize Orbit checklist and execute the burn at the next Ap passing.
Roger! Let's circularize this orbit!
Orbit is circular within mission requirements.
Roger, great job, main objective is complete!
Not bad, the next item on our flight plan is to start preparing for the retrograde burn.

We wish to splash down in the Atlantic, so our retrograde burn should be on the west coast of the U.S. Using the Orbital Cursor on Orbit View (F3), press C to toggle the Orbital Cursor, then drag the slider so it's position is above the coast.

Still looking at the map view, we will timescale until we have passed the orbital cursor before proceeding. This is because we want to have a full orbit of preparation time for entry. Press ROGER when you have passed the orbital cursor.
Then get back into the cockpit view, and request that our retrograde burn should happen on the orbital cursor point. Press ROGER when you have done so.
We should now have a retrograde burn time. We will start the retrograde checklist 30 minutes before ignition.
We are 30 minutes from retrograde burn. Proceed with the PRE RETRO checklist using the RUN feature.
Going through the checklist now.
Checklist complete.
Roger, then run the 256 SEC TO RETRO checklist.
When running the checklist, follow the Event Timer marks and complete the checklist. Press PRO on the last step.
Complete the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist and complete the burn.
Adapter is separated.
Roger adapter separation.
Retros are burning! Follow the checklist to complete the burn and retro jettison.
Retros jettisoned, please complete the POST-RETRO JETTISON checklist.
Ok, this is it. We are soon entering the atmosphere.
Doing great, time flies when in space.
Good luck with entry. If you feel you have the time and control, perform some slight RCS movements to ensure jet temperatures are good.
Roger. See you on the inside.
Ok, building up. Hold tight, this will be a different type of ride.
Roger, can't wait for some fresh sea air.
We got this.
Roger.
This is {{capsuleName}}, do you read?
...--- clear, sure -- is .... see you! ... ..-- visual.
We hear you 1/5, can you repeat?
Ok, we have contact. Follow the landing checklist and prepare for drogue release.
Roger! Great to see you, we have a visual. Welcome home!
Roger. Performing landing checklist.
There goes the drogue!
Roger drogue! Prepare for main.
We see the mains, set landing attitude and prepare for splashdown.
Roger. Recovery close?
On their way, not too far, we still see you.
Roger.
Splash!
Ok, that was great!
Indeed it was. MCC, we have splashdown, everything is good.
Roger, welcome home, hope the boat floats if you know what I mean. There's a lot of happy faces down here, can't wait to see you guys.
Thanks! I believe the score of firsts has increased to 4 - 1 now?
Yes indeed. You beat me 3 - 1 in Project Mercury, I have not forgotten that.
I bet you haven't.
I'll see you both soon, this is MCC signing out, recovery will take over. (Transmission ends)

Title: A NEW SPACECRAFT
Description: The new Gemini spacecraft is ready for its maiden flight, and the flight has been assigned to you and your crew. The goal is to test some of its core systems, and its maneuvering capabilities.
BriefingText:
The Gemini capsule is designed to carry a crew of two into orbit, and has the capability of changing its attitude in all axes, as well as maneuvering in all axes.
By carefully maneuvering in a given direction at the correct time, with a predefined burn length, we will be able alter the orbital trajectory of the craft.

Before attempting this mission, please complete the Gemini Academy.

Ingress: T-90 minutes
Cockpit setup: Cold & Dark

This first Gemini mission has the following primary objectives:
1) Ascend into a predefined target orbit:
Perigee 161 km altitude
Apogee 225 km altitude
Inclination 28.91 degrees

2) Execute a burn at the first Perigee passing to circularize the orbit to:
Perigee 161 km altitude*
Apogee 161 km altitude*
Inclination 28.91 degrees

*If deviations on insertion exists, these parameters will be slightly different.

3) Safely splash down in the Atlantic ocean.
